<DIV style="position:absolute;top:158;left:482"><nobr><span class="ft17"><b>WINDOWS</b></span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:188;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft6">The Windows OOB Server uses the application event log to record<br>status, diagnostic, and security information. Events logged by the<br>OOB Server include the following:</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:269;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:269;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft3">The OOB Server was started, stopped, paused, or resumed.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:302;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:302;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft6">An attempt was made to access the OOB Server or a data<br>source that was disallowed by an access control rule.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:359;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:359;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft6">An attempt was made to access a Web Administrator page that<br>was disallowed because an invalid user name or password was<br>supplied.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:440;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:440;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft3">The OOB Server caught an exception.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:473;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft5">Much of the information written to the application event log is also<br>written to the OOB Server log files (by default, these are stored in<br>the c:\temp directory). Refer to the application event log if:</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:554;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:554;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft5">The standard OOB auditing mechanism wasn’t enabled for the<br>period that you’re interested in.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:611;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:611;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft6">You prefer to examine log file entries by using Event Viewer<br>rather than a text editor.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:668;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft17"><b>To view the application event log</b></span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:701;left:232"><nobr><span class="ft3">1. Do one of the following:</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:734;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:734;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft5">In <b>Control Panel</b>, open <b>Administrative Tools</b>, then open <b>Event</b><br><b>Viewer</b>.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:791;left:261"><nobr><span class="ft3">•</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:791;left:288"><nobr><span class="ft6">For Windows NT, click <b>Start, </b>click <b>Programs</b>, click<br><b>Administrative Tools</b>, and then click <b>Event Viewer</b>.</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:848;left:232"><nobr><span class="ft3">2. In the left hand pane of the <b>Event Viewer </b>window, click <b>Application</b>.</span></nobr></DIV>
</DIV>
